[[File:German - Jug with a Bridge Spout - Walters 482089.jpg|thumb|16th-century German [[stoneware]] jug]] [[File:Nazca - Lobster Effigy Vessel - Walters 20092055.jpg|thumb|Nazca, effigy vessel formed as a [[lobster]], AD 300–600 (Early Intermediate Phases IIII–IV)]] A '''bridge-spouted vessel''' is a particular design of [[ewer]] ([[jug]] or [[pitcher (container)|pitcher]]) originating in antiquity; there is typically a connecting element between the spout and filling aperture, and the spout is a completely independent aperture from the usually smaller central fill opening. Early incidences of the bridge spouted vessel are found in [[Persia]] in the early [[Iron Age]]<ref>[https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/search.aspx?searchText=bridge-spouted British Museum "Bridge spout"] on collection database</ref> and on [[Crete]]. This type of vessel typically appears in the [[Bronze Age]] or early [[Iron Age]]. A very early example of a bridge spouted bowl has been recovered at the ancient [[palace]] of [[Phaistos]] on [[Crete]], dating to the [[Bronze Age]].<ref>[http://www.themodernantiquarian.com/site/10881/cydonia.html#fieldnotes C.Michael Hogan, ''Phaistos Fieldnotes'', The Modern Antiquarian (2007)]</ref>
There is a different type, characteristic of the pottery of the [[Nazca culture]] of [[Pre-Columbian]] [[Peru]], where two spouts rising vertically from the body of the vessel are linked by a bridge that apparently also served as a carrying handle.
