[[File:La Democracia 2.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.7|Prehispanic sculpture on display at the entrance to the museum]]
The '''Museo Regional de Arqueología de la Democracia''' ("Regional Archaeological Museum of La Democracia") is an archaeological museum in the [[Municipalities of Guatemala|municipality]] of [[La Democracia, Escuintla|La Democracia]] in the [[Departments of Guatemala|department]] of [[Escuintla Department|Escuintla]] in [[Guatemala]].<ref name="REDCAMUS">REDCAMUS.</ref> The museum displays [[Pre-Columbian era|pre-Columbian]] [[Mesoamerica]]n artefacts from the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]] lowlands  datingfrom the [[Mesoamerican chronology#Preclassic Era or Formative Period|Preclassic Period]] through to the [[Mesoamerican chronology#Postclassic Era|Postclassic Period]], with a particular emphasis upon the local [[Monte Alto culture]].<ref name="REDCAMUS"/> The museum is open from Tuesday through to Saturday from 8am to 4pm.<ref name="REDCAMUS"/>

==Location==
The museum is situated opposite the central park of La Democracia, which is notable for its display of large prehispanic sculptures in the [[Potbelly sculpture|potbelly]] style.<ref name="REDCAMUS"/> La Democracia is situated in the department of Escuintla at an altitude of {{convert|165|m|ft}} [[above mean sea level]].<ref name="INFORPRESSCA">INFORPRESSCA.</ref> It is {{convert|92|km|mi}} from Guatemala City.<ref name="REDCAMUS"/> The local climate is hot, with an average temperature of {{convert|35|C|F}}.<ref name="INFORPRESSCA"/>

==History==
The museum was founded in February 1966 at the instigation of Rubén Chévez van Dorne, who had regularly been given pre-Columbian ceramic pieces by teachers working on a [[cotton plantation]] in the neighbouring municipality of [[La Gomera, Escuintla|La Gomera]], who observed that archaeological remains were frequently uncovered by tractors.<ref name="MCD97p1">Ministerio de Cultura y Deportes c.1997, p.1.</ref> The museum was placed in a school building that was refurbished by [[INGUAT]], the Guatemalan Institute of Tourism; it had previously housed the Escuelas Urbanas de la Democracia.<ref name="MCD97p1"/> The museum opened its doors on 22 May 1972.<ref name="MCD97p1"/> As part of the refurbishment, Guatemalan artist Guillermo Grajeda Meno painted 21 murals within the museum.<ref name="MCD97p1"/>

==Collection==
Aside from its archaeological collection, the museum possesses an exhibition of modern art by Guatemalan artists, displayed on the upper floor.<ref name="REDCAMUS"/> The museum also holds a collection of historical books and documents.<ref name="REDCAMUS"/> The anthropomorphic sculpture of a head outside the museum entrance was loaned for two months for display at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York.<ref>Chévez van Dorne 1978, 1999, pp.19, 25.</ref>

